1. Introduction

Unsupervised learning techniques are widely used across various domains such as business, finance, healthcare, environmental science, and more to extract valuable insights from data. This project aims to apply key unsupervised learning methods and tools to address real-world problems effectively.

The project is divided into two parts, each containing two studies, using a recommendation dataset as the basis for analysis.

  • Part 1 explores clustering algorithms and collaborative filtering recommendation systems:

    • The first study focuses on clustering, where K-Means and DBSCAN algorithms will be tested. Their performance will be evaluated using visual inspection techniques to determine the most suitable method for the given dataset.

    • The second study involves building a collaborative filtering-based recommendation system, which will be assessed through both qualitative and quantitative evaluations to measure its effectiveness.

  • Part 2 delves into similarity measures and content-based recommendation systems:

    • The third study investigates various similarity measures, examining their impact on classifying the dataset and their role in improving recommendation performance.

    • The final study involves developing a content-based recommendation system, leveraging domain-specific heuristics to enhance recommendations.

Each step of this project is fully reproducible and well-documented to facilitate understanding. To avoid execution errors, it is recommended to run the notebook cells sequentially from top to bottom.

2. Preparation of the data

In this section, I will introduce the Anime Recommendation Dataset selected for the upcoming studies. I will first explore the dataset, conduct validity checks on its features, and identify any inconsistencies. Then, I will perform outlier detection and removal before applying feature engineering techniques to refine the dataset and prepare it for analysis.

A. Dataset presentation : Anime Recommendations Database

This dataset contains information on user preference data from 73,516 users on 12,294 anime. Each user is able to add anime to their completed list and give it a rating and this data set is a compilation of those ratings.

  • Anime.csv
    • anime_id - myanimelist.net's unique id identifying an anime.
    • name - full name of anime.
    • genre - comma separated list of genres for this anime.
    • type - movie, TV, OVA, etc.
    • episodes - how many episodes in this show. (1 if movie).
    • rating - average rating out of 10 for this anime.
    • members - number of community members that are in this anime's "group".
  • Rating.csv
    • user_id - non identifiable randomly generated user id.
    • anime_id - the anime that this user has rated.
    • rating - rating out of 10 this user has assigned (-1 if the user watched it but didn't assign a rating).

In[3]:
# The first step is to handle missing values of the dataset
# I am going to use the Machine Learning based functions from LightGBM to impute the missing values of the dataset
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestRegressor, RandomForestClassifier

# This function factorizes the dataframe by turning cateorical features into numerical features
def factorize(df):
    df_copy = df.copy()
    for cat_col in df_copy.select_dtypes(include=object):
        df_copy[cat_col] = pd.factorize(df_copy[cat_col])[0]
    return df_copy

# This function creates splits of the dataset, one for training and the other one for testing. To use in issing values imputation functions
def create_splits(df, col):
    train = df[df['is_nan'] == 0]
    test = df[df['is_nan'] == 1]

    X_train = train.drop([col, 'is_nan'], axis=1)
    y_train = train[col]
    X_test = test.drop([col, 'is_nan'], axis = 1)
    return X_train, y_train, X_test

# The function responsible for training the model and return the imputed missing values as predictions 
# I am using the default settings here to build the predictive models that I am going to use to impute the missing values
def train_predict(mode, X_train, y_train, X_test):
    # Select model based on mode
    if mode == 'regression':
        model = RandomForestRegressor(n_estimators=100, max_depth=10, random_state=42)  # Default settings
    else:
        model = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=100, max_depth=10, random_state=42)

    # Train the model
    model.fit(X_train, y_train)

    # Predict missing values
    y_pred = model.predict(X_test)
    
    return y_pred
    
# The function that I am going to use to impute the missing values of numerical features
def impute_missing_values(df, cols_lst, mode):
    
    
    for col in cols_lst:
        # Drop the column if there are more than 50% of missing values
        if df[col].isnull().sum() > int(len(df)/2):
            df.drop(col, axis=1, inplace=True)
            print(f'Dropped {col} because it has more than 50% of the data missing')
        else:
            data = df.copy() # I am going to change the subset of the dataset for training and I don't want to change the original dataset
            # creating a new column 'is_nan' set to 1 for each row having a missing value on the 'col" attribute
            nan_indexes = data[data[col].isna()].index
            data['is_nan'] = 0
            data.loc[nan_indexes, 'is_nan'] = 1

            # Factorizing categorical features
            data_f = factorize(data.drop([col], axis=1))
            data_f[col] = data[col]
    
            # splitting the subset into into a train and testing set to train the model for missing values imputation
            X_train, y_train, X_test = create_splits(data_f, col)
    
            #Training the model using LGBMRegressor and impute missing values
            y_pred = train_predict(mode, X_train, y_train, X_test)
    
            #Now let's include the imputed values into the original dataset at the correct 
            if pd.api.types.is_integer_dtype(df[col]):  # If the column is originally integer
                df.loc[nan_indexes, col] = y_pred.astype(int)  # Convert predictions to int
            elif pd.api.types.is_float_dtype(df[col]):  # If the column is originally float
                df.loc[nan_indexes, col] = y_pred.astype(float)  # Ensure predictions remain float
            else:
                df.loc[nan_indexes, col] = y_pred  # Default case

    return df

# The second step involves removing outliers
# I am going to use the Z-score method to detect the outliers in the different numerical features of the two datasets
from scipy import stats

def remove_outliers(df, attr):
    z_scores = np.abs(stats.zscore(df[attr]))
    df = df[z_scores <= 3]
    return df
    
anime = remove_outliers(anime, "rating")
anime = remove_outliers(anime, "members")
anime = remove_outliers(anime, "episodes")

# I am first going to display the functions of the different validity checks to perform (Uniqueness, Look-up errors check and Exact duplicates check)

# The function that checks for unique values
def check_unique(df, attr):
    duplicates = df[df.duplicated(subset=[attr], keep='last')]
    return duplicates.index

# The function find_exactDuplicates will do exactly what his name stands for lol. 
def find_exactDuplicates(df):
    df = df.drop_duplicates(keep = False)
    return df

# The function Look_up that takes the attribute and a table of acceptable values in parameters
def look_up( df, attr, acc_values):
    invalid_indexes = df.index[~df[attr].isin(acc_values)]
    return invalid_indexes

2. Studies

Study 2 - Clustering Algorithms

The goal of this study is to explore and compare two clustering algorithms: KMeans and DBSCAN. These methods will be applied to a selected subset of data from the previous study, using different attribute combinations for analysis.

In this study, we will test multiple variations of each algorithms parameters. For KMeans, we will examine at least two different values for k to assess their impact on cluster formation. For DBSCAN, we will experiment with at least two values for eps and min_samples, which influence the density required to form a cluster.

Since clustering relies on a similarity measure, we will limit the analysis to two attributes at a time, making it easier to visually interpret the results. We will illustrate the obtained groupings using visualizations, allowing for an intuitive evaluation of cluster quality.

Finally, we will compare the performance of KMeans and DBSCAN based on visual inspection of the clusters and, optionally, on metrics such as cluster magnitude and cardinality. The objective is to determine which algorithm is more appropriate given the structure of the data and the observed clustering results.

from sklearn.metrics import silhouette_score as ss
# Train the KMeans model
def make_kmeans_clusters(df, X, k):
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state=42, n_init=10)
    clusters = kmeans.fit_predict(X['x'])

    # Add cluster labels to the original dataset
    df.loc[:,"Cluster_kmean"] = clusters

    # Calculate the silhouette score to evaluate the KMeans clustering approach
    score = ss(X['x'], clusters)
    print(f' The Silhouette score is {score}')

    # Visualize clusters
    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
    X_d = X['x']
    subset = X['subset']
    sns.scatterplot(x=X_d[:, 0], y=X_d[:, 1], hue=clusters, palette="viridis")
    plt.xlabel(subset[0])
    plt.ylabel(subset[1])
    plt.title("KMeans Clustering")
    plt.legend(title="Cluster")
    plt.show()

  • Analysis

For the KMeans clustering approach, the silhouette scores varied depending on the value of k. After testing different values (k = 5, k = 10, and k = 3), the highest silhouette scores were obtained with k = 3, reaching 0.41 to 0.47 for X1 (Episodes Rating) and 0.43 to 0.50 for X2 (Rating Members).

These results indicate that a 3-cluster solution provides the best-defined grouping within the dataset. However, the silhouette scores suggest moderate cluster separation, meaning that while some clusters are well-formed, others may overlap or contain points that are not strongly associated with their assigned cluster. The slightly higher scores for X2 indicate that clustering based on Rating and Members yields a more meaningful separation compared to Episodes and Rating.

Although k = 3 was the optimal choice, the fact that the scores remained below 0.50 suggests that KMeans may not be the best fit for this dataset. This could be due to overlapping clusters, irregular cluster shapes, or variability in feature distributions. In the next steps, I will compare these results to DBSCAN and explore whether alternative feature transformations or a different similarity measure can enhance clustering performance

b. DBSCAN clustering Analysis

In[19]:
from sklearn import metrics
from sklearn.cluster import DBSCAN


def make_dbscan_clusters(X_d, eps, min_samples):
    X = X_d['x']
    subset = X_d['subset'] 
    db = DBSCAN(eps=eps, min_samples=min_samples).fit(X)
    labels = db.labels_

    # Count clusters & noise
    n_clusters_ = len(set(labels)) - (1 if -1 in labels else 0)
    n_noise_ = np.sum(labels == -1)

    # Evaluate the clusters
    score = ss(X, labels)
    print(score)
    
    # Plot clusters
    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
    unique_labels = set(labels)
    colors = [plt.cm.Spectral(each) for each in np.linspace(0, 1, len(unique_labels))]
    
    for k, col in zip(unique_labels, colors):
        if k == -1:
            col = [0, 0, 0, 1]  # Black for noise
    
        class_member_mask = labels == k
        plt.scatter(X[class_member_mask, 0], X[class_member_mask, 1], 
                    c=[tuple(col)], edgecolors="k", s=50, label=f"Cluster {k}")
    
    plt.title(f"DBSCAN Clustering (Clusters: {n_clusters_}, Noise: {n_noise_})")
    plt.xlabel(subset[0])
    plt.ylabel(subset[1])
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()

To refine my clustering approach, I will implement a Grid Search strategy in the next step. This will allow me to systematically explore different parameter values and identify the optimal configuration that maximizes the silhouette score. By fine-tuning the clustering parameters, I aim to achieve a better-defined structure before applying my clustering function to X2, the second feature subset used for similarity measurement.

In[21]:
import itertools
# the function get_best_dbcan will perform different dbscan clustering algorithms (with different combinations of parameters) and return the model that had the best silhouette score.
def get_best_dbscan(X):
    best_score = -1.0
    best_labels = [] # We are going to use this variable to get the labels of the best clustering model the first time that it ran.
    best_model = DBSCAN() # we are gonoing to return this variable at the end after trying the different versions and finding the best
    
    # The combinations of parameters to try
    eps_tab = np.linspace(0.01, 1, num=10)
    min_samples = np.arange(2, 20, step=3)
    combinations = list(itertools.product(eps_tab, min_samples))
    N = len(combinations)

    # The Grid Search execution starts here
    for i, (eps, num_samples) in enumerate(combinations):
        dbs_model = DBSCAN(eps=eps, min_samples=num_samples).fit(X)
        labels = dbs_model.labels_
        labels_set = set(labels)
        num_clusters = len(labels_set)
        if -1 in labels_set: # To remove the noise cluster
            num_clusters -= 1
        # We want to ignore bad clustering results
        if (num_clusters < 2) or (num_clusters > 50):
            c = (eps, num_samples)
            print(f"Combination {c} on iteration {i+1} of {N} has {num_clusters} clusetrs. Moving on")
            continue

        current_score = ss(X, labels)
        if current_score > best_score:
            best_labels = labels
            best_score = current_score
            best_model = dbs_model

    return { 'best_score': best_score,
            'best_labels': best_labels,
            'best_model': best_model}

# Visualizing the clusters after our Grid Search
def visualize_clusters(X_d, labels):
    X = X_d['x']
    subset = X_d['subset']

    # Count clusters & noise
    n_clusters_ = len(set(labels)) - (1 if -1 in labels else 0)
    n_noise_ = np.sum(labels == -1)

    # Plot clusters
    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
    unique_labels = set(labels)
    colors = [plt.cm.Spectral(each) for each in np.linspace(0, 1, len(unique_labels))]
    
    for k, col in zip(unique_labels, colors):
        if k == -1:
            col = [0, 0, 0, 1]  # Black for noise
    
        class_member_mask = labels == k
        plt.scatter(X[class_member_mask, 0], X[class_member_mask, 1], 
                    c=[tuple(col)], edgecolors="k", s=50, label=f"Cluster {k}")
    
    plt.title(f"DBSCAN Clustering (Clusters: {n_clusters_}, Noise: {n_noise_})")
    plt.xlabel(subset[0])
    plt.ylabel(subset[1])
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()

c. Clustering algorithms analysis conclusion

In this study, we explored two clustering algorithmsKMeans and DBSCANto segment anime data based on different feature subsets: (Episodes Rating) and (Rating Members). Our goal was to evaluate the effectiveness of each algorithm using silhouette scores and visual inspection of the resulting clusters.

Key Findings:

  • KMeans produced moderate silhouette scores, with the best results obtained at k = 3 (0.410.47 for X1 and 0.430.50 for X2). While the clusters were somewhat distinct, the lower scores suggest overlapping clusters and potential misclassification of some points.

  • DBSCAN, on the other hand, yielded a stronger silhouette score of 0.65 after fine-tuning parameters through a Grid Search approach. This suggests that DBSCAN found more meaningful clusters with clearer separation, outperforming KMeans in terms of cluster quality.

  • Visual inspection reinforced these resultsDBSCAN formed densely packed clusters while filtering out noise points, whereas KMeans struggled with well-defined boundaries, likely due to the nature of the dataset and the presence of non-spherical clusters.

Final Verdict:

  • Overall, DBSCAN appears to be the better choice for this dataset, as it effectively identified well-separated clusters and handled noisy data points more effectively than KMeans. While KMeans was able to provide a structured partitioning, its performance was limited by overlapping clusters and moderate silhouette scores.

  • Moving forward, further feature engineering, dimensionality reduction (PCA, t-SNE), or alternative distance metrics could be explored to improve clustering results even further. Nonetheless, this study highlights the importance of choosing the right clustering algorithm based on both quantitative metrics and visual inspection rather than relying solely on a predefined method like KMeans.

Study 4 - Collaborative Filtering Recomendation System

In this study, we will develop a recommendation system based on collaborative filtering. The foundation of this approach lies in constructing the utility matrix (Rui matrix), where user ratings are used to infer preferences without relying on item metadata.

To generate recommendations, we will perform Matrix Factorization by decomposing the utility matrix into two lower-dimensional matrices, P and Q, which will help approximate missing ratings. We will explore different values for the latent dimension to assess their impact on recommendation quality.

For qualitative evaluation, we will simulate recommendation requests for three users, retrieving items they would likely rate highly but have not yet interacted with.

For quantitative evaluation, we will implement a Gold Standard (GS) testing approach by removing 10% of the ratings and comparing predicted ratings against actual values. We will evaluate performance using:

  • Mean Squared Error (MSE) to measure the accuracy of predicted scores.

  • Precision@K (P@5, P@10) and Mean Reciprocal Rank (MRR) after transforming ratings into a binary relevance system.

The results of these evaluations will provide insights into the effectiveness of our collaborative filtering model and its ability to generate meaningful recommendations.

B. Implementing the recommendation system based on collaborative filtering

In[15]:
## The Matrix factorization function that is going to use to produce collaborative filtering based predictions
# This function is inspired from the function implememted by Denise Chen (the function can be found in the article "Recommender System  Matrix Factorization" - See Reference at the end of the notebook)
def matrix_factorization(R, P, Q, K, steps=30, alpha=0.1, beta=0.2):
    '''
    R: rating matrix
    P: |U| * K (User features matrix)
    Q: |D| * K (Item features matrix)
    K: latent features
    steps: iterations
    alpha: learning rate
    beta: regularization parameter'''
    Q = Q.T

    for step in range(steps):
        for i in range(len(R)):
            for j in range(len(R[i])):
                if R[i][j] > 0:
                    # calculate error
                    eij = R[i][j] - np.dot(P[i,:],Q[:,j])

                    for k in range(K):
                        # calculate gradient with a and beta parameter
                        P[i][k] = P[i][k] + alpha * (2 * eij * Q[k][j] - beta * P[i][k])
                        Q[k][j] = Q[k][j] + alpha * (2 * eij * P[i][k] - beta * Q[k][j])

        eR = np.dot(P,Q)

        e = 0

        for i in range(len(R)):

            for j in range(len(R[i])):

                if R[i][j] > 0:

                    e = e + pow(R[i][j] - np.dot(P[i,:],Q[:,j]), 2)

                    for k in range(K):

                        e = e + (beta/2) * (pow(P[i][k],2) + pow(Q[k][j],2))
        # 0.001: local minimum
        if e < 0.001:

            break

    return P, Q.T

# Convert actual ratings to binary relevance (1 = relevant, 0 = irrelevant)

predictions_df['predicted_binary'] = predictions_df['predicted'].apply(lambda x: 1 if x >= 4 else 0)
  • We calculate Precision at K (P@K) for the top K recommended items for each user. Precision is the proportion of relevant items in the top K recommendations.
In[]:
def precision_at_k(predictions_df, k=5):
    # Sort predictions by predicted score for each user
    predictions_df_sorted = predictions_df.sort_values(by='predicted', ascending=False)

    # Select the top K predictions
    top_k = predictions_df_sorted.head(k)

    # Calculate Precision at K
    relevant_count = sum(top_k['predicted_binary'])
    return relevant_count / k

# Calculate Precision at 5 and 10
P_at_5 = precision_at_k(predictions_df, k=5)
P_at_10 = precision_at_k(predictions_df, k=10)

print(f"Precision at 5 (P@5): {P_at_5}")
print(f"Precision at 10 (P@10): {P_at_10}")
  • The Mean Reciprocal Rank (MRR) measures the rank position of the first relevant item in the list of recommendations.
In[]:
def mean_reciprocal_rank(predictions_df):
    # Find the rank of the first relevant item (binary relevance = 1)
    predictions_df_sorted = predictions_df.sort_values(by='predicted', ascending=False)
    relevant_ranks = predictions_df_sorted[predictions_df_sorted['predicted_binary'] == 1].index

    if len(relevant_ranks) > 0:
        return 1 / (relevant_ranks[0] + 1)  # Rank starts at 0, so we add 1 to avoid division by zero
    return 0

# Calculate MRR
MRR = mean_reciprocal_rank(predictions_df)
print(f"Mean Reciprocal Rank (MRR): {MRR}")

3. Conclusion

This study focused on building a collaborative filtering recommendation system using matrix factorization on a large user-item rating dataset. The process involved constructing a sparse user-item matrix, applying matrix factorization to approximate missing ratings, and evaluating the model using metrics like Mean Squared Error (MSE), Precision at K (P@K), and Mean Reciprocal Rank (MRR).

Key challenges included handling the large dataset, addressing its sparsity, and optimizing matrix factorization for better scalability. Despite efforts, memory and computational limitations required working with a smaller dataset for training. The use of a Gold Standard (GS) created by removing 10% of ratings allowed for effective evaluation of the system's predictive accuracy.

While the study demonstrated the value of matrix factorization and evaluation metrics, it also highlighted the need for more efficient algorithms and scalability solutions, such as distributed computing or advanced optimization techniques, to handle large-scale datasets in real-world recommender systems.
